Customizing Plots

We now know how to create many plot types using ggplot2, but often you want to customize your plots. Today, well discuss common tools for customizing our plots.

To begin, make sure that you have the tidyverse loaded.

library(tidyverse)

Also, lets start with our plot from the exercise

scorecard <- read_csv("https://github.com/cmsc205/data/raw/master/ScorecardSmallNarrow.csv")
# Code for your solution to the warm up exercise
# Let's assign the plot ot the object p
p <- scorecard %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = ADM_RATE, y = net_cost)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, color = "steelblue") +
  geom_smooth(color = "black", se = TRUE) +
  facet_grid(CONTROL ~ income_group)
p

Adding titles, axis labels, and legend labels

Good labels are critical for making your plots accessible to a wider audience. Its important to ensure axis and legend labels display the full variable name (or a logical abbreviaition), but this does not always happen by default.

To add/alter these annotations we simply add a new layer using the labs function.

Adding a title

# Code for adding a title to a plot
p <- p + labs(title = "Average Next Cost per Year at U.S. Colleges")
p

Adding a subtitle

# Code for adding a subtitle to a plot
p <- p + labs(subtitle = "By income quintile")
p

Changing the axis labels

# Code to change axis labels
p <- p + labs(x = "Admissions rate, %",
         y = "Net cost per year, $'000")

Changing the legend labels

# Code to change legend labels
scorecard %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = ADM_RATE, y = net_cost, color = ADM_RATE)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_smooth(color = "black", se = TRUE) +
  facet_grid(CONTROL ~ income_group) + 
  labs(color = "Admissions\nRate")

Ordering factors

Sometimes we need to order the levels of a factor to make a plot meaningful.

To examine this, lets look at a new data set which contains informatio on the 10 most popular baby names in 2014.

babynames <- read_csv("https://github.com/cmsc205/data/raw/master/top10babynames2014.csv")
# Let's work with this bar chart of the top 10 baby names in 2014
babynames %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = name, y = n, fill = sex)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip()

To do this with respect to another variable we can use the reorder function.

# Reordering the names by popularity in the bar chart
babynames$name <- reorder(babynames$name, 
                          FUN = function(x) -identity(x), 
                          babynames$n)
p2 <- babynames %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = name, y = n, fill = sex)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Baby Names in 2014",
       x = NULL,
       y = "Count")

Choosing color palettes

ggplot2 does not choose the nicest looking palettes, and the palettes are typically not colorblind friendly. Luckily, its quite easy to change the color palettes you use.

Manual adjustments

To manually adjust the colors we can use the functions scale_color_manual or scale_fill_manual

# Code to manually adjust the plot colors
p2 + scale_fill_manual(values = c("turquoise", "gold"))

Using RColorBrewer

You can let the RColorBrewer package choose the colors for you using the scale_color_brewer and scale_fill_brewer functions.

# Code to use the scale_fill_brewer function
p2 + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

You can see all of the possible palettes in the package by running

rr RColorBrewer::display.brewer.all()

Using viridis

If you install the viridis package (this might not be on the server), then you can use the scale_color_viridis and scale_fill_viridis functions.

# Example of how to use the viridis color scheme with a discrete variable
library(viridis)
p2 + scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE)

A colorblind friendly palette

The ggthemes package contains a colorblind-friendly palette, which can be adopted using the scale_color_colorblind and scale_fill_colorblind functions.

# Using the colorblind friendly palette in ggthemes
library(ggthemes)
p2 + scale_fill_colorblind()

Choosing themes

By default ggplot2 uses a grey background and guidlines on a plot; however, we dont always want our plots to appear this way. To change this the appearance, we need to work with themes.

The ggthemes package offers many additional choices.

We can use an existing theme just like adding a layer.

# Let's check out the minimal theme first to remove many features
p + theme_minimal()

# Let's pick another theme from the list
p + theme_tufte()

Customizing themes

Sometimes the ggthemes package wont do exactly what you want so you will have to dig into ggplot2 a bit deeper and create your own theme.

See ?theme for a list of all of the components that you can modify.
